INCE the close contact of the heart and lungs

in man has probably been a source of error, as I have said, the common practice of anatomists, in dogmatizing on the general make-up of the animal body, from the dissections of dead human subjects alone, is objectionable. It is like devising a general system of politics, from the study of a single state, or deigning to know all agriculture from an examina· tion of a single field. It is fallacious to attempt to draw general conclusions from one particular proposi- tion.

If only anatomists were as familiar with the dis- section of lower animals as with that of the human body, all these perplexing difficulties would, in my opinion, be cleared up.
